'''Suginohara no Ota-mai''' (杉野原の御田舞) is a folk performance tradition from {{ill|Aridagawa, Wakayama|ja|有田川町|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Arida District, Wakayama|ja|有田郡|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, in {{ill|Wakayama Prefecture|ja|和歌山県|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Japan. It has been designated an {{ill|Important Intangible Folk Cultural Property|ja|重要無形民俗文化財|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
In the town, historically significant as a {{ill|post town|ja|宿場町|qq=draft|qq=draft}} on the routes to {{ill|Mount Kōya|ja|高野山|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and the Ryūjin pilgrimage paths, many {{ill|cultural properties of Japan|ja|文化財|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and traditional folk performances have been preserved.
The Ota-mai, derived from {{ill|Dengaku|ja|田楽|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, evolved into a ritual celebrating agricultural abundance. It was practiced in nine villages along the {{ill|Aridagawa River|ja|有田川|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, formerly called Tokugawa. Suginohara’s Ota-mai, performed biennially on {{ill|February 11|ja|2月11日|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, takes place at the {{ill|Amitabha Hall of Amijaku-ji Temple|ja|雨錫寺阿弥陀堂|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the only remaining medieval-style stage in the region. The event reenacts over 20 steps of the rice production cycle, from plowing to milling, in a dramatized instructional exchange between a father-in-law and his son-in-law. The performance begins with the vigorous "Hadaka Nae-oshi" (裸苗押し), where robust men in loincloths lock arms, drum, and engage in energetic pushing and grappling to the rhythm of chants and music.
Suginohara no Ota-mai is notable for depicting the entire rice production process, including harvest, which is rare among {{ill|Ota (ritual)|ja|御田|1=Sacred rice field|qq=draft|qq=draft}} performances in Japan, most of which conclude at the planting stage. Alongside the {{ill|Hanazono no Ota-mai|ja|花園の御田舞|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Katsuragi, Wakayama|ja|かつらぎ町|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, it is a distinctive and valuable tradition unique to this region. == See Also == * {{ill|Theatre of Japan|lt=Theatre of Japan|lt=Traditional performing arts of Japan|ja|伝統芸能|en|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
