{{afc comment|Wikidata entry [[d:Q11522359]] Wikidata name: (none) [[User:Immanuelle|Immanuelle]] ([[User talk:Immanuelle|talk]]) 09:33, 11 June 2025 (UTC)}} '''Suginohara no Ota-mai''' (杉野原の御田舞) is a folk performance tradition from [[:en:Aridagawa, Wakayama|Aridagawa, Wakayama]], [[:en:Arida District, Wakayama|Arida District, Wakayama]], in [[:en:Wakayama Prefecture|Wakayama Prefecture]], Japan. It has been designated an {{ill|Important Intangible Folk Cultural Property|ja|重要無形民俗文化財|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Important Intangible Folk Cultural Property|qq=}}.
In the town, historically significant as a {{ill|Shukuba|lt=Shukuba|lt=Post town|ja|宿場町|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/post town|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 宿場}} on the routes to [[:en:Mount Kōya|Mount Kōya]] and the Ryūjin pilgrimage paths, many [[:en:Cultural Property (Japan)|cultural properties of Japan]] and traditional folk performances have been preserved.
The Ota-mai, derived from [[:en:Dengaku|Dengaku]], evolved into a ritual celebrating agricultural abundance. It was practiced in nine villages along the {{ill|Aridagawa River|ja|有田川|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Aridagawa River|qq=}}, formerly called Tokugawa. Suginohara’s Ota-mai, performed biennially on [[:en:February 11|February 11]], takes place at the {{ill|Amitabha Hall of Amijaku-ji Temple|ja|雨錫寺阿弥陀堂|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Amitabha Hall of Amijaku-ji Temple|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, the only remaining medieval-style stage in the region. The event reenacts over 20 steps of the rice production cycle, from plowing to milling, in a dramatized instructional exchange between a father-in-law and his son-in-law. The performance begins with the vigorous "Hadaka Nae-oshi" (裸苗押し), where robust men in loincloths lock arms, drum, and engage in energetic pushing and grappling to the rhythm of chants and music.
Suginohara no Ota-mai is notable for depicting the entire rice production process, including harvest, which is rare among {{ill|Ota (ritual)|ja|御田|1=Sacred rice field|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ota (ritual)|13=User:Immanuelle/Sacred rice field|qq=}} performances in Japan, most of which conclude at the planting stage. Alongside the {{ill|Hanazono Onta-mai|lt=Hanazono Onta-mai|lt=Hanazono no Ota-mai|ja|花園の御田舞|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hanazono no Ota-mai|qq=}} in [[:en:Katsuragi, Wakayama|Katsuragi, Wakayama]], it is a distinctive and valuable tradition unique to this region. == See Also == * {{ill|Theatre of Japan|lt=Theatre of Japan|lt=Traditional performing arts of Japan|ja|伝統芸能|en|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Theatre of Japan|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 日本の伝統芸能}}
